  [ordered]@{
    category = $catTravel
    sourceUrl = "https://www.business-standard.com/immigration/thailand-ends-60-day-visa-free-entry-in-major-tourism-policy-rollback-126052000243_1.html"
    sourceTitle = "Thailand ends 60-day visa-free entry in major tourism policy rollback"
    sourceBody = "Thailand is ending a 60-day visa-free entry policy in a move with implications for tourism demand and travel planning."
    publishedAt = "2026-05-20 12:20:00"
    generatedTitle = "Thailand Cuts Visa-Free Stay Window in Policy Shift That May Reshape Travel Plans"
    body = "Thailand is ending its 60-day visa-free entry policy in a major rollback that could alter travel planning for international visitors and reshape demand in parts of the tourism sector. The change matters because Thailand has become one of the region's most important destinations for budget travelers, remote workers and long-stay visitors who often build flexible itineraries around entry rules. Tourism operators and immigration analysts say the adjustment will force airlines, hotels and independent travelers to reassess how long trips can realistically be planned without additional paperwork, particularly for visitors who had come to rely on generous short-term access.`n`nThe policy shift arrives at a sensitive moment for tourism recovery and regional competition. Southeast Asian destinations have spent years trying to rebuild traveler confidence, restore route capacity and attract both leisure visitors and longer-stay guests who contribute more to local spending. Entry rules are therefore not just administrative details; they are part of the commercial offer a country presents to the global market. Even a modest reduction in flexibility can influence how travelers compare destinations when budgets, schedules and work arrangements are still unsettled.`n`nFor airlines and accommodation providers, the immediate issue is predictability. Short-stay tourists may not be strongly affected if the new rule still covers ordinary vacations, but longer itineraries become more complicated when visitors must factor in visa applications, documentation or the risk of overstaying. Travel advisors note that policy simplicity often shapes booking behavior more than governments expect. When travelers perceive uncertainty, they may shorten trips, choose a different country or postpone plans altogether.`n`nThe impact may be especially notable among digital nomads and slow-travel segments. These groups tend to value destinations where they can combine affordable living, reliable infrastructure and flexible entry conditions. Thailand has been one of the biggest beneficiaries of that pattern, with many travelers building month-long or multi-city stays around easy access. A narrower visa-free window may not eliminate demand, but it could redirect a share of it toward places seen as administratively easier.`n`nOfficials and industry representatives will likely argue that immigration control, compliance and capacity management also matter. Governments must balance tourism growth with concerns around informal work, overstays and enforcement. From that perspective, tightening entry rules can be framed as an effort to align policy with administrative reality rather than as a rejection of tourism itself. The challenge is that policy messages are interpreted through traveler psychology, not only through government intent, and tourism markets tend to react quickly to perceived friction.`n`nHotels, local businesses and transport providers are therefore watching closely to see how the change affects booking patterns. If the policy pushes travelers toward shorter, higher-frequency visits, some segments may adapt without major disruption. If it reduces Thailand's appeal for longer stays, however, the effect may be felt more broadly across rental markets, co-working spaces, regional tourism circuits and small hospitality operators who depend on extended visitor spending.`n`nThe broader lesson is that travel policy now sits at the center of destination competition. In a market where visitors compare rules as closely as prices and attractions, visa access becomes part of tourism branding. Thailand remains a major destination with strong cultural appeal, infrastructure and global recognition, but the rollback is a reminder that even established tourism leaders must consider how policy signals influence traveler behavior. Over the coming months, the real test will be whether the new entry rules are seen as manageable adjustment or as a friction point that changes where people choose to go."
    imagePrompt = "Professional editorial photograph of an international airport departures hall with travelers checking passports and luggage under bright travel signage, Southeast Asia setting, 16:9 aspect ratio, no text, no watermark, no logo."
    generatedBy = "model"
